The paper deals with the problem of computing spectral approximations to graphs in a dynamic streaming model, which involves processing a stream of edge insertions and deletions to a graph. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. However, the paper's focus on spectral sparsification and effective resistance embedding of graphs suggests that it is more closely related to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Numerical Analysis (cs.NA), or Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper's use of linear sketching and ball-carving techniques suggests that it may also be relevant to the Signal Processing (cs.SP) or Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Overall, we believe that cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.IT, cs.NA, and cs.CG are the most likely sub-categories for this paper.
